Title:
CowSpot: Real-time Module Stomping Detection

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post describes a defensive technique (“CowSpot”) for detecting module stomping in real time on Windows, where an attacker overwrites the in-memory code of a legitimately loaded module to hide malicious execution.  
- The problem addressed is that traditional detections often rely on post-compromise memory scans or coarse indicators, while module stomping can evade file-based and some behavioral controls.  
- It focuses on monitoring memory protection changes and write activity to executable-backed image regions (e.g., PE sections mapped from disk) and correlating those events with suspicious execution from the modified pages.  
- The write-up discusses practical implementation considerations such as identifying image-backed regions, handling legitimate JIT/self-modifying patterns, and reducing false positives.  
- It’s primarily useful for Blue Teams/EDR engineers and detection researchers building telemetry-driven detections; Red Teams can use it to understand what behaviors their in-memory tradecraft exposes.  
- It’s interesting because it targets a common in-memory evasion primitive with event-driven detection rather than periodic scanning, improving time-to-detect.

Technical Focus:
- Windows module stomping / image-backed memory tampering
- Virtual memory protections and page permission transitions (RW→RX, etc.)
- Monitoring writes to PE image sections in process memory
- Execution-from-modified-page correlation (write-then-execute patterns)
- EDR-style telemetry design and false-positive reduction

Use Cases:
- Build EDR detections for overwrite-of-module code sections (inline replacement)  
- Hunt for in-memory implants that masquerade inside signed/legit DLLs  
- Validate whether offensive loaders/injectors trigger write+execute telemetry  
- Create lab PoCs to test detection coverage for module stomping variants  
- Develop SOC playbooks for triaging suspicious memory modification events

Keywords:
module stomping, Windows, in-memory evasion, PE image, DLL, memory tampering, VirtualProtect, NtProtectVirtualMemory, WriteProcessMemory, page protections, RWX, write-then-execute, EDR telemetry, memory forensics, code injection, reflective techniques, section overwrite, image-backed memory, detection engineering